    <!-- SECTION 1: INTEGRATION LEADERSHIP & EXPERTISE -->
    <section>
      <div class="container--default">
        <p class="section-label fade-in">Integration leadership &amp; expertise</p>
        <h2 class="section-title fade-in">The case for integration as a discipline</h2>

        <div class="services-grid fade-in">

          <div class="service-card" style="border-top-color:var(--color-node-blue); grid-column:auto; display:block;">
            <p class="service-card-number">Paper &middot; <em>Sustainability Science</em> 20, 95–115 &middot; 2025 &middot; Open access</p>
            <h3>"Herding Cats": Integrative Leadership Strategies in ITD Research Programs</h3>
            <p>Deutsch, Björnsen Gurung, Defila, Di Giulio, Hoffmann &amp; Scholz. Drawn from in-depth study of three Swiss ITD research programs, this paper identifies six core leadership challenges: mastering complexity and ambiguity, lateral decision-making, ensuring accountability, setting boundaries, selecting suitable projects, and correcting misconceptions about what integration work entails. Makes a clear empirical case that leading an ITD programme is a specialist skill requiring distinct competencies — not generic research management.</p>
            <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11625-024-01585-4" class="service-card-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              DOI: 10.1007/s11625-024-01585-4
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

          <div class="service-card" style="border-top-color:var(--color-node-green); grid-column:auto; display:block;">
            <p class="service-card-number">Paper &middot; <em>Humanities and Social Sciences Communications</em> 9, 1 &middot; 2022 &middot; Open access</p>
            <h3>Integrate the Integrators! A Call for Establishing Academic Careers for Integration Experts</h3>
            <p>Hoffmann, Deutsch, Thompson Klein &amp; O'Rourke (Nature Portfolio). Argues that despite integration being the central challenge of ITD research, academia offers no recognised career path for people who do it. Proposes four concrete remedies: a Community of Practice, empirical study of successful integration careers, dedicated funding lines, and sustained dialogue with universities and funders. The intellectual foundation of the ITD Alliance's working group on integration experts.</p>
            <a href="https://doi.org/10.1057/s41599-022-01138-z" class="service-card-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              DOI: 10.1057/s41599-022-01138-z
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

          <div class="service-card" style="border-top-color:var(--color-node-purple); grid-column:auto; display:block;">
            <p class="service-card-number">Blog post &middot; i2Insights &middot; June 2023 &middot; Free</p>
            <h3>Towards a Theory of Change to Institutionalise Integration Experts and Expertise</h3>
            <p>The Aeschiried Integrators. Maps a concrete pathway from the current situation — where integration expertise is largely invisible and career trajectories are blocked — to a future in which universities establish permanent positions for integration experts. Articulates specific milestones (2025: awareness among university leadership; 2032: critical mass of positions established), typologises cousin roles (knowledge brokers, boundary spanners, i2S specialists), and frames integration as a rigorous and distinct methodology.</p>
            <a href="https://i2insights.org/2023/06/06/institutionalising-integration-expertise/" class="service-card-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              Read on i2Insights
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

          <div class="service-card" style="border-top-color:var(--color-node-amber); grid-column:auto; display:block;">
            <p class="service-card-number">Paper &middot; <em>PNAS</em> 121(32), e2402646121 &middot; 2024 &middot; Open access</p>
            <h3>Slow Convergence: Career Impediments to Interdisciplinary Biomedical Research</h3>
            <p>Berkes, Marion, Milojević &amp; Weinberg. Analyses 154,021 biomedical PhD holders over four decades to show that the most interdisciplinary researchers stop publishing within eight years — compared to over twenty years for disciplinary peers. Provides large-scale quantitative evidence that current career structures actively select against those who cross disciplinary boundaries, making the empirical case for structural change in how interdisciplinary research is supported and evaluated.</p>
            <a href="https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.2402646121" class="service-card-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              DOI: 10.1073/pnas.2402646121
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

          <div class="service-card" style="border-top-color:var(--color-node-red); grid-column:auto; display:block;">
            <p class="service-card-number">Paper &middot; <em>Higher Education Research &amp; Development</em> &middot; 2024</p>
            <h3>Why and How Academics Become Interdisciplinary Researchers Early in Their Careers</h3>
            <p>Taylor et al. Qualitative study identifying six distinct pathways through which early- and mid-career researchers enter interdisciplinary work — all characterised by ad hoc navigation rather than deliberate institutional support. Finds that universities lack consistent approaches to developing interdisciplinary skills beyond isolated PhD programmes, and that this gap is most acutely felt in the early career stages when collaborative research norms are first being established.</p>
            <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/07294360.2024.2332255" class="service-card-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              DOI: 10.1080/07294360.2024.2332255
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

          <div class="service-card" style="border-top-color:var(--color-node-blue); grid-column:auto; display:block;">
            <p class="service-card-number">Survey report &middot; Leiden Madtrics / LERU &middot; 2021 &middot; Free</p>
            <h3>Skill Gaps of PhD Graduates: The Largest Gaps Are in Teamwork and Social Skills</h3>
            <p>Survey of 2,193 recently graduated PhDs from Dutch universities, finding that the largest reported skills gaps are in teamwork, social skills, and project management — precisely the competencies required for collaborative, cross-disciplinary research. PhDs report being well-trained in discipline-specific methods but underprepared for the interpersonal and organisational dimensions of research careers in complex collaborative settings.</p>
            <a href="https://www.leidenmadtrics.nl/articles/skill-gaps-of-phd-graduates" class="service-card-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              Read report
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

