    <!-- SECTION 2: FRAMEWORKS & METHODS -->
    <section class="integration-section">
      <div class="container--default">
        <p class="section-label fade-in">Frameworks &amp; methods</p>
        <h2 class="section-title fade-in">How integration actually works</h2>

        <div class="services-grid fade-in">

          <div class="service-card" style="border-top-color:var(--color-node-green); grid-column:auto; display:block;">
            <p class="service-card-number">Book &middot; ANU Press &middot; 2013 &middot; Free open-access e-book</p>
            <h3>Disciplining Interdisciplinarity: Integration and Implementation Sciences for Researching Complex Real-World Problems</h3>
            <p>Gabriele Bammer. Foundational text for the field of Integration and Implementation Sciences (i2S). Builds the case for a new research discipline — comparable to statistics in its breadth of application — dedicated to synthesising knowledge across disciplines, managing unknowns, and translating research into policy and practice change. The three core i2S domains and fifteen guiding questions provide the intellectual scaffold on which subsequent tools, frameworks, and training programmes in the field are built.</p>
            <a href="https://doi.org/10.22459/DI.01.2013" class="service-card-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              DOI: 10.22459/DI.01.2013 &middot; Free e-book
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

          <div class="service-card" style="border-top-color:var(--color-node-purple); grid-column:auto; display:block;">
            <p class="service-card-number">Blog post &middot; i2Insights &middot; April 2024 &middot; Free</p>
            <h3>Integration and Implementation Sciences (i2S) 3.0: An Updated Framework</h3>
            <p>Gabriele Bammer. The latest iteration of i2S, revised to reflect current thinking on addressing complex societal and environmental problems. Describes three domains of expertise — understanding problems comprehensively, supporting policy and practice change, and enabling effective interactions — and positions i2S specialists as the "statisticians of complexity". Shorter and more immediately usable than the 2013 book, and the best current entry point into the framework.</p>
            <a href="https://i2insights.org/2024/04/16/i2s-updated-framework/" class="service-card-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              Read on i2Insights
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

          <div class="service-card" style="border-top-color:var(--color-node-amber); grid-column:auto; display:block;">
            <p class="service-card-number">Blog post &middot; i2Insights &middot; September 2021 &middot; Free</p>
            <h3>Transdisciplinary Integration: A Multidimensional Interactive Process</h3>
            <p>Fam, Thompson Klein, Hoffmann, Mitchell &amp; Pohl. An authoritative synthesis — written by leading figures in the field — of what integration actually means in transdisciplinary research: a multidimensional, iterative process of weaving, balancing, and accommodating different knowledge systems. Cuts through the vagueness that often surrounds the term and provides a shared vocabulary for designing, describing, and evaluating integration work in research projects.</p>
            <a href="https://i2insights.org/2021/09/14/transdisciplinary-integration/" class="service-card-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              Read on i2Insights
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

          <div class="service-card" style="border-top-color:var(--color-node-red); grid-column:auto; display:block;">
            <p class="service-card-number">Blog post &middot; i2Insights &middot; May 2017 &middot; Free</p>
            <h3>Methods for Integration in Transdisciplinary Research</h3>
            <p>Bergmann et al. A structured catalogue of 43 integration methods grouped into seven epistemological classes — from conceptual clarification and joint problem framing to formal model building and process-based cooperation instruments. Establishes that integration is not improvised facilitation but a methodologically grounded practice with an identifiable repertoire of techniques that can be learned, adapted, and evaluated.</p>
            <a href="https://i2insights.org/2017/05/09/transdisciplinary-integration-methods/" class="service-card-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              Read on i2Insights
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

          <div class="service-card" style="border-top-color:var(--color-node-blue); grid-column:auto; display:block;">
            <p class="service-card-number">Online toolbox &middot; td-net / Swiss Academies of Arts &amp; Sciences &middot; Free</p>
            <h3>The td-net Toolbox for Co-Producing Knowledge</h3>
            <p>Twenty tested tools for co-producing knowledge in transdisciplinary research, covering the full project lifecycle — from jointly framing problems with stakeholders to exploring pathways to impact. Developed by the Swiss Network for Transdisciplinary Research (td-net), tested across dozens of projects, and used in university and doctoral training internationally. Bridges the gap between abstract integration frameworks and day-to-day facilitation practice.</p>
            <a href="https://naturalsciences.ch/co-producing-knowledge-explained/methods/td-net_toolbox" class="service-card-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              Open toolbox
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7"/></svg>
            </a>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

